doc.ContractDescription: IGF::OT::IGF SMA FOR CHOIR SERVICES AT THE CHAPEL

GOALS AND OBJECTIVES: THE PRIMARY OBJECTIVE OF THIS WORK IS TO DEVELOP AN IMPROVED DESCRIPTION OF SOLAR WIND EXPANSION ABOVE THE TRADITIONAL SOURCE SURFACE HEIGHT (AT 2.5 SOLAR RADII). WE WILL FOCUS ON KEY MEASUREMENTS THAT ARE REQUIRED TO CONSTRAIN MODELS FOR THE SLOW SOLAR WIND AND CORONAL HOLE/STREAMER INTERFACE (CSIF) REGIONS. THE TERM CSIF IS USED TO DESCRIBE, GENERALLY, THE EDGES OF STREAMERS WHICH CAN INCLUDE THE STREAMER STALK AND THE POORLY UNDERSTOOD TRANSITION REGION BETWEEN THE EDGE OF THE STREAMER AND THE CORONAL REGIONS WHERE FAST SOLAR WIND ORIGINATES. DURING THE COURSE OF THIS WORK, WE WILL ADDRESS THREE MAIN SCIENCE QUESTIONS: 1) WHAT ARE THE MOST IMPORTANT PARAMETERS THAT CONTROL THE SPEED VARIABILITY OF THE SLOW SOLAR WIND? 2) WHAT IS THE LATITUDINAL EXTENT OF THE SLOW SOLAR WIND FROM THE CSIF BOUNDARY? (WE WILL ALSO INVESTIGATE WHETHER THE TRANSITION BETWEEN THE SLOW WIND NEAR THE CSIF BOUNDARY AND THE FAST WIND IS SHARP OR GRADUAL.) 3) WHICH PLASMA AND MAGNETIC FIELD CONDITIONS DETERMINE THE STABILITY OF STREAMERS AND THE CHARACTERISTICS OF STREAMER BLOBS? APPROACH: WE WILL USE EXISTING CORONAGRAPH AND MAGNETOGRAPH DATA SETS TO CONSTRAIN CORONAL PLASMA AND MAGNETIC FIELD PARAMETERS OF THE SLOW WIND FROM CSIF REGIONS BETWEEN 2.5 AND 3.5 SOLAR RADII. THESE INCLUDE THE SPATIAL DISTRIBUTION OF ELECTRON DENSITIES, PROTON TEMPERATURES AND OUTFLOW VELOCITIES FOR THE PLASMA; AND THE FIELD STRENGTHS, ORIENTATION, AND FLUX TUBE EXPANSION FACTORS FOR THE CORONAL MAGNETIC FIELD. THE SPATIAL VARIATIONS OF THESE PARAMETERS AND THEIR RELATIONSHIPS DERIVED FROM BASIC PHYSICAL CONSERVATION LAWS WILL BE USED TO TEST SOME CRITICAL FEATURES FROM CURRENT SLOW SOLAR WIND AND STREAMER MODELS. THE EMPHASIS ON LATITUDINAL RATHER THAN THE RADIAL VARIATIONS OF THE PLASMA AND MAGNETIC FIELD PARAMETERS IS PARTICULARLY USEFUL FOR UNDERSTANDING THE CSIF REGIONS, ESPECIALLY THE TRANSITION FROM SLOW TO FAST SOLAR WIND. SCIENCE IMPACT AND RELEVANCE: THIS WORK WILL ADDRESS THE CORONAL ORIGINS OF THE SLOW SOLAR WIND AND WILL SHED LIGHT ON WHETHER THE SLOW WIND COMES FROM PRIMARILY OPEN FIELD REGIONS ALONG CSIF BOUNDARIES OR FROM MAINLY CLOSED FIELD REGIONS INSIDE OF STREAMERS/ACTIVE REGIONS. IF THE SLOW WIND SOURCE REGIONS CAN BE IDENTIFIED WITH A PARTICULAR TYPE OF MAGNETIC FIELD CONFIGURATION ON THE SUN, THIS WILL PROVIDE VALUABLE GUIDANCE FOR THEORETICAL SOLAR WIND MODELS. IN ADDITION, SINCE CORONAL MASS EJECTIONS (CMES) ARE OFTEN EMBEDDED WITHIN THE SLOW WIND/CSIF REGIONS, UNDERSTANDING THIS REGION WILL BE USEFUL FOR MODELING THE PROPAGATION OF CMES, A MAJOR SOURCE OF SPACE WEATHER. IN TERMS OF BENEFITS TO FUTURE NASA PROGRAMS, THE EXPECTED RESULTS CAN BE USED TO PREPARE FOR FUTURE IN SITU OBSERVATIONS OF THE NEAR-SUN REGIONS BY SOLAR ORBITER AND SOLAR PROBE PLUS.
